==Old English==
===Etymology===
From Germanic ''*bazā-'', from Indo-European ''*bhos-''.

''Germanic cognates:'' Old Frisian [[bar]], Old Saxon [[bar]] (Dutch [[baar]]), Old High German [[bar]] (German [[bar]]), Old Norse [[berr]] (Norwegian [[berr]], Swedish [[bar#Swedish|bar]])

''Indo-European cognates:'' Slavic ''*bosъ'' (Russian [[босой]], Polish [[bosy]]), Baltic ''*basa-'' (Lithuanian [[basa|bãsa]], Latvian [[bass]])

===Pronunciation===
[[IPA]]: /bæɹ/

===Adjective===
'''bær'''
# [[bare]], [[naked]], [[unconcealed]]
#:''Wit her baru standaþ unwered wædo'': we stand here naked, unprotected by garments.  (Cædmon's ''Metrical Paraphrase'')

